  <span id="freeText1198988542616983665" style="display:none">Beautifully written and absorbing novel. It is so rich in detail and yet nothing is superfluous; it is a story that deals with the real fundamentals of life -faith, hope and love. <br /><br />Jacob is committed to God. Even as a slave, he tries to observe all of the Jewish laws and customs. He is committed to his eternal life despite all manner of distractions: brutal living conditions, pagan influence and sexual desire. I was struck by the contrast between the pagans who were also considered Gentiles and this Jew. The discipline of the Jew in sharp contrast to the pagans who live to survive and satisfy their animal instincts caused me to reflect upon the divine purpose of a chosen people. What could compel a people to look past their own animal instincts, if not God? And yet this story offers a deeper exploration of the Jewish faith in relation to the law. It shines a light on Jews who claim their inheritance by birthright by following the letter of the law but routinely violating the spirit of it. Jacob sees it and it repulses him in the same way as the Bolshevik atrocities (hard to stomach at times) and the undisciplined animal ways of the Gentiles. <br /><br />It is a story of hope. Jacob never loses hope in God. There is a point when Wanda becomes more than just an object of desire. Even Jacob seems to realize the Divine Hand at work, especially in returning to Wanda. I think this Divine Hand was in spite of the sorcery employed by Wanda. The theme of hope was especially strong towards the end of the story, when Jacob must go on alone. Can't say much more without giving away too much but hope is definitely present. At least twice characters note "those who want to die never do." Even these statements reminded me of the biblical idea that death is still the enemy. <br /><br />And love. The story is indeed a beautiful love story. For me, the beauty lies in the complexity of their love. It was a sacrificial love. The sacrifice may appear to be one sided with Wanda leaving behind so much of her historical self to unite with Jacob however given Jacob's exalted role within his community, he also sacrificed. I loved the whole transcendence of this love story. It has a sort of Divine order set against the particular brutal time of 17th century Poland. I am not sure that I have sufficient knowledge of the Jewish faith to appreciate the conversion and the ramifications of the comment " Jewish soul". However I think the book explores the divine nature of love in a most subtle and satisfying way. <br /><br />I think I could read this several times over and find new wisdom every time. </span>
