  <span id="freeText5154370246878243227" style="display:none">This is a fascinating and nuanced work by a Nobel Prize winning 20th century writer of Jewish-themed novels who reaches for a big-picture historical/theological/philosophical perspective. <br /><br />On the surface, this is the story of a doomed love between a Jew who is captured and sold into slavery following at 16th Century pogrom and falls in love the with daughter of his master. But Romeo and Juliet, this isn’t. The situation faced by the Jewish community in Europe in the centuries following the post-Roman era dispersion is front and center and as one who knows anything about history might expect, it’s dismal and dangerous. What’s really noteworthy here is that as bad as the Jews in this novel have it, Poland, the place where it’s set, was actually one of the better places for Jews to live back then (which says something about how bad other places were).<br /><br />But it wasn’t simply Jews/Good-Gentiles/Bad. The novel is much more challenging than that and really makes you work it you want to set up a good guys versus bad guys ledger. There are Jews and Gentiles in both columns.<br /><br />The only thing that disappointed me was the last quarter of the book. Once the major even toward which the novel was building occurred (I won’t mention it to avoid spoilers), all of the nuance and grabbed hold of me up till then vanished as Singer switched gears, threw subtlety out the window, and raced toward a romantic fairy tale ending.</span>
