  <span id="freeText14761781259477950385" style="display:none">The Slave is one of Bashevis Singer's strongest novels, and a good place to start if you have never read any of his books - if only because it is a short novel. It's also wonderfully well written, reflective and strongly felt. <br />Several of Bashevis Singer's novels share a pattern: a man intends to be good but finds himself is drawn into love by his emotions. Choosing to be true to himself, he diverges from conventional Jewish virtue and encounters a new intensity of suffering that leads him more deeply into life. He responds with a fresh turn towards righteousness and ends with a hard-won wisdom before he dies as some kind of a saint.<br />In his book on Shakespeare, Ted Hughes - venturing that every writer has only one fundamental story to tell - cites Bashevis Singer, suggesting that he found us story in writing Satan in Goray, has first published novel. The Slave is set in the same period: the aftermath of the Chmielnicki massacres of 1648, which devastated Polish Jewry and foreshadowed The Holocaust. Jacob the protagonist, is learned Jew who has been enslaved by Polish peasants, and falls in love with Wanda, a beautiful gentile. The book charts his journey as well as evoking the Jewish past. <br />The historical setting also allows Singer to explore the mental world that traditional Jews had inhabited, in which the Bible and Talmud were intertwined with daily life, and the universe was suffused by angels, dybbuks and a phantasmagoria of saints and miracles. That's what I find most alluring in the world this book creates: what was it like to inhabit such a universe, even as it collided with historical catastrophe and the moral failings of ordinary Jews? We usually think of Singer as a Jewish novelist, but this is also historical fiction and it shames most other novels in that genre with the depth of its imagining and the immediacy with which it shows how people think, how they feel and why they act as they do. </span>
