<span id="freeTextContainer6613210231383764007">Better as Short Stories<br/><br/>Everything Singer wrote is creatively interesting with the added depth of historical context, but these components are unable to “salvage” this novel, which is repetitive, includes too many anecdotes and minor details about Jewish and Polish peasant life that distract from the main story, and becomes boring as Joseph constantly torments himself how to justify his passion for a gentile woman. The intriguing details about Polish peasant superstitions and licentious behavior </span>
  <span id="freeText6613210231383764007" style="display:none">Better as Short Stories<br /><br />Everything Singer wrote is creatively interesting with the added depth of historical context, but these components are unable to “salvage” this novel, which is repetitive, includes too many anecdotes and minor details about Jewish and Polish peasant life that distract from the main story, and becomes boring as Joseph constantly torments himself how to justify his passion for a gentile woman. The intriguing details about Polish peasant superstitions and licentious behavior seem anthropological, as do Singer’s factoids about life in small Jewish villages constantly being attacked by Cossacks and warring European nations. Now that such cultures and behaviors have vanished, his detailed descriptions of peasants’ often savage and even pagan behavior provide an interesting glimpse into the dark, cruel life Jacob lived as a slave of these peasants.<br /><br />While the novel may be valuable to students of folklore, pagan peasant life, Jewish history, and even theological issues, as Jacob cites numerous Jewish texts to examine his situation and help him decide what he can do and whether this would be acceptable, his unique situation, where he’s pursued by and loves a Polish peasant girl, is outside both Polish and Jewish laws and cultural norms. Thus it is inherently unlikely, except that Jacob’s return from slavery is during the period of messianic fervor surrounding Sabbati Zevi, who used obscure cabbalistic writings to support his ideas that upended traditional Jewish religious, social and sexual norms. Singer hints at this when he says Jacob’s “investigations of the cabala since his return [from slavery] had uncovered the doctrine that all lust was of divine origin…Coupling was the universal act underlying everything…God’s holy names themselves were mysterious unions of the male and female principles” (111). Only at the novel’s end does Singer reveal that Jacob and his equally devout son for a time had belonged to Zevi’s sect. For more background on this interesting movement, Singer’s fascinating novel Satan in Goray (1933) is a detailed, compelling description of this exceptional period in the 1650s and 60s when a Jewish peasant mania occurred because Zevi convinced many that he was the Messiah and the End of Days was about to happen, after which Jews would magically fly to Israel and no longer suffer persecutions, such as Chmielnicki had caused in 1648.<br /><br />Between 1648 and 1655 as many as 100,000 Jews were tortured, massacred and their property confiscated or destroyed, and Jacob frequently hears about specific atrocities. The Chmielnicki massacre occurs at the beginning of this novel, after which Jacob is abducted by bandits who sell him to the Poles, and he enter slavery for six years. He is ransomed and returns to his Jewish village; after several years (during which Zevi mania was spreading) he goes in search of the faithfully waiting Wanda, who easily agrees to go with him. One of the signs of the End of Days was that among the mystical happenings many Christians converted to Judaism, either out of conviction or because they too wanted to escape miserable poverty and fly to Israel. Thus marriages of gentiles and Jews would signify the Redemption was at hand. “Entire communities of Jews turned Christian and though some later resumed their own faith, others remained in darkness” (122). His conversion of Sarah he thinks of as having “saved a soul from idolatry” (132), and when he says that now she is completely separated from her family, and Jacob is her only relative, she demands that her beloved father also be taken into paradise or she won’t go (133). Perhaps this background explains why Wanda agrees to convert when the penalty was being burned alive, and why Jacob would think a converted gentile might be accepted by his Jewish community. By the time she dies in childbirth, he is convinced that his marriage and her “conversion” are in violation of all laws, and his sin has resulted in her murder, although later as a Zevi devotee his attitude changes. Such reversals occur throughout, and Singer never explores why she would agree to marry Jacob except that she had seen him in a vision and had a mystical conviction she is fated to be joined to him, which, coupled to her passionate love, provides a sentimentally satisfying explanations. <br /><br />There are many redundant, obscure sections where Jacob agonizes over his situation, torn between his passion and lust, which Jewish tradition considers are sinfully caused by Satan, and his obsession with following all Jewish rules and precepts. He constantly questions whether a true conversion can be based upon love, which is the only factor that can motivate a woman (only men can make a religious decision), and examines exceptional situations, many of which come from cabbalistic writings, as possible models for his behavior. The beginning of the final section “The Return” goes into limited detail about Zevi’s cabbalistic ideas, which caused some to cease “to follow the Torah, believing the law would be annulled with the coming of the Messiah. Still others ferreted out hints in the Bible that to be utterly evil was the way to redemption, and they indulged in every variety of abomination” (232). After Sarah’s death and Jacob’s migration to Israel, during the period of Messianic fervor their union came to symbolize the “physical action” that Zevi encouraged, and their intermarriage fulfilled texts that suggested “Jacob and Sarah as precursors of the Redemption” (239); for a time her grave was treated as a holy site by local women, until Zevi’s conversion to Islam (1666), when his followers were scorned and excommunicated. <br /><br />These ideas and texts are unknown to the average reader, so most of this analysis is of little general interest and probably more confusing and problematic than useful for the narrative. The same could be said of Jacob’s tormented analysis of the Torah and other Jewish texts to find explanations that would justify converting and marrying Wanda, as well as provide answers to basic questions why evil is permitted, what is the nature of God, and is there eternity, most of which are unanswerable and some border on blasphemy for the devout, who are encouraged not to question. The reason for Jacob’s manic focus on such issues is that he was always an aloof, quiet misfit. who refused charity and took on hard physical labor, atypical for any Jew aspiring to scholarly status, although Jacob always carefully avoided this identification despite his intense love of books. He “had his own ways of thinking and acting,… interpreted the Torah in his own manner, was accustomed to suspicion and mockery. Even as a child he had been a misfit” (241). Because Singer places this information at the end of the novel, it is barely interesting and makes Jacob seem a different person from the man in the first two parts. In the end, the novel seems like a fanciful description of an ideal marriage that units passion to devotion, combines some gentile common sense with obedience to important Jewish principles, ended by a brief declaration of why Jacob acted as he did that may explain his idiosyncratic behavior. <br /><br />Because Jacob is determined not to reject his heritage (one of the novel’s leitmotifs), even though his looks and speech would enable him easily to pass as gentile (only his circumcision would mark him as Jewish), in the end Wanda must convert, which involves not only endless study of Jewish religious rules but also having to play “dumb” because she can never speak Yiddish without being identified as gentile. Jacob asks her to make a much greater sacrifice than he makes in marrying her. After the ridicule she suffers from her Jewish neighbors, who criticize and mock her “handicap,” her horrible death in childbirth, and unsanctified burial, his shame and remorse for asking her to make such sacrifices may be the reasons he takes his infant son and follows a disciple of Zevi to Israel, where a new approach to Judaism seemed to be flourishing that was free of the restrictions, intolerance and impiety he had always experienced. Singer implies rigid traditions allowed many who weren’t truly pious and faithful to the spirit of Judaism to pass as pious because they devoted their attention to the laws’ minutiae. “His years away from the Torah had changed his views. Now conscious of much he had not realized, he saw that one law in the Torah generated a dozen in the Mishnah, and five dozen in the Gemara…Each generation added its own strictures…A new thought occurred to him: if this continued, nothing would be kosher” (99). Jacob and Sarah frequently wonder how Jews can consider themselves pious and yet behave cruelly to fellow Jews; Jacob often mentions this hypocrisy when he describes people’s hostile, exclusionary attitude toward him and Sarah, as well as toward poor people generally. His quandary is underlined when he’s teaching the converted Sarah about Jewish laws: “The sacred books warn that all those who gossip, ridicule, or speak evil of others, will burn in the fires of Gehenna.” She says Jewish women frequently break these laws and yet refuse to eat pork, so these must be lesser sins. All Jacob can reply is, “That’s the way it’s always been…It’s easier not to eat pig than to curb your tongue” (135). <br /><br />Strict Jewish laws, difficult to challenge because of their traditional, religious weight, at first make it impossible for the devout Jacob to accept his passionate nature. Instead of freely accepting Wanda’s complete love, he constantly critiques her peasant circumstances, although acknowledging she’s much above the peasant norm. “The peasants here had not even risen to the level of the Christians. They still followed the customs of the ancient pagans” (12), which are described in lurid detail. Jewish family and community practices, established by religious texts, are presented as superior to both. At points Jacob seems almost arrogant when he cannot make any attempt to join with Wanda’s family in celebrations because the food isn’t kosher, or there are other activities such as dancing and singing that are forbidden. While many of the peasants are depicted as truly offensive and evil, Jacob’s stern rejection of even simple gentile pleasures seems excessively rigid. Only once does he feel pity for “a monstrous, square-headed girl with a goiter on her neck…compassion for this creature…deformed and misshapen, a mooncalf, swept over Jacob. Who could tell…what sinful soul had been incarcerated in the girl’s body. Hers was not an ordinary cry but the wail of a spirit who has gazed into the abyss and seen a torment from which there is no escape. Through some miracle this animal comprehended its own bestiality and mourned its lot” (53). In the end he’s fearful what the girl might do to him, so he avoids her. Although at times the peasants ask Jacob to come and live with them, he scorns their offer as contamination, and unfortunately his firm rejection of contact only increases their hostility, even though Singer intends it to show Jacob’s religious faithfulness even under extreme circumstances.<br /><br />The novel’s major conflict is simple: how can two people, who love each other, be married when both their communities prohibit such a marriage upon penalty of death. Frequently Jacob goes over the catalog of Biblical Jewish men who had affairs or married gentiles. Even so, he isn’t confident God will excuse him or Sarah for their sin of marrying. This insoluble problem occupies him throughout the novel, and it becomes truly irritating to hear him trying to find excuses, then discarding them, but all the while acknowledging that he and Sarah are happy despite all the trials. While his undying struggle to justify his marriage probably appeals to Romantic Jewish readers, for many others these trials seem the result of outdated traditions, narrow cultural norms, and societal constraints that for the most part have thankfully vanished. Perhaps this is why Singer is attracted to the period of Sabbati Zevi, when precisely such narrow, rigid Jewish traditions were challenged and sometimes discarded. However, the movement resulted in abuses and ultimately achieved nothing, although for a brief period it provided Jews different options for their religious practices. <br /><br />Since Wanda is unconcerned about giving up Christianity and says from the first that she’s eager to convert, her problem is easily resolved. Jacob, however, splits another hair and worries that her desire for conversion is the result of her love for him and not her devout decision directed by God. In addition, she knows neither Yiddish (the language spoken by the Jews) nor anything about their religious rituals and traditional customs, which are complex and control every aspect of their lives. If Singer hadn’t pointed out that the Torah promulgates codes of behavior that are more “advanced” in terms of community organization, sanitation and food handling than those practiced at the time by pagan peasants or even the average Christians, the contemporary reader might think Wanda’s decision to adopt Judaism would result in more restrictions than advantages. <br /> <br />When Jacob is enslaved, he lives in the mountains where his master, Wanda’s father, sends him to tend his cows during the summer, and despite his enslavement, he finds joy in simple, natural events, like a glorious sunrise or patterns of light in the trees or birdsong each morning. “A hawk, wings outstretched, glided tranquilly with a strange slowness beyond all earthly anxieties. It appeared to Jacob that the bird had been flying without interruptions since creation” (10). In a sense, this is an Eden, distant from brutal Polish life and the quarrelsome, restrictive Jewish existence. He doesn’t regret his stay on the mountains, except that he has none of his religious books and has a hard time following the Jewish calendar to celebrate holy days correctly, which ironically will immerse him in all the anxieties of Jewish life. On his later return to get Wanda, he notes that the fresh air and beauty of the countryside are a welcome contrast to the constraints in a Jewish community where he was shut up daily reading books. “How beautiful the countryside was…Doubt, dissension, discord dwelt within him, but the fields exuded harmony, tranquility, fruitfulness. The sky was blue, the weather warm with the mercy of summer… A hidden hand had shaped and modeled each stalk, blade of grass, leaf, worm” (104). It is mainly at moments when he can look at the stars in the night sky and see there almost a cabalistic text of God’s ultimate control and goodness that he is most at peace. “The summer night throbbed with joy; from all sides came music. Warm winds bore the smells of grain, fruit, and pine trees to him. Itself a cabalistic book, the night was crowded with sacred names and symbols--mystery upon mystery…The stars looked like letters of the alphabet, vowel points, notes of music..The world was a parchment scrawled with words and song…He was surrounded by powers, some good, some evil, some cruel, some merciful, but each with its own nature and its own task to perform…The struggle was going on without as well as within him” (163). In this sensual environment, Wanda is a great temptation, which he valiantly resists. It’s amusing that when he won’t take the first step, she proposes marriage to him, he rejects her proposal because of his religion, she offers to co-habit with him, which is standard practice among her peasant neighbors, and although Jacob is tempted by this idea, fornication is also forbidden by Jewish law. So he resists mightily, until the inevitable happens one rainy night. Then she willingly undergoes cleansing rituals in a frigid mountain stream as her first demonstration what she’s willing to do for him.<br /><br />Critiques of Jewish practices occur when Jacob is working for the debauched aristocrat, Adam Pilitzky, who quizzes him about Jewish behavior and beliefs, starting with Jacob’s refusal to drink wine with him because his religion forbids it. Singer gives many shocking details about the Pilitzkys’ sexual practices to show them as deviant, corrupt, incompetent, and in need of Jewish tenants to do the work on their lands, although some Jews employed by Pilitzky are no better ethically. While Pilitzky has some tolerance toward Jews who work on his land and create his wealth, he’s quite rigid that only Catholics are Christians, while Orthodox and Protestant don’t qualify. He questions Jacob sharply as to why Jews stubbornly refuse to eat foods or intermarry, believe they are a chosen people, yet are impoverished and constantly suffering. Christians “suffer for a reason. Our souls are purified through what we endure and rise to heaven” (154). Adam recounts that he heard ecstatic singing in the synagogue, but later Jews crushed each other to death when the Cossacks arrived. “Where was the God you praise and beseech, whose dear children you claim to be? How do you deal with these facts, Jew? How can you sleep at night remembering” (154). Adam’s wife says that Christians too have no answer to this. “Even searching for an answer is blasphemous” (154), and Adam grasps at Democritus’ idea that “chance ruled everything…The world…was the result of blind powers” (155). Ironically, he obsessively hopes to see a miracle to convince him there is a God, which would give him a reason to live. <br /><br />After Sarah dies in an appalling, naturalistically described childbirth that goes on for many pages, Jacob meets one of Zevi’s apostles, who are wandering around trying to convert people. Perhaps Jacob’s attraction to Zevi is due to feeling lonely and exiled from all Jews, as well as overwhelmed with sorrow by Sarah’s death. In any case, Jacob’s life in Pilitz ends with him taking his infant son and leaving for Israel. Between her death and the third section, twenty years pass during which Jacob has become one of Zevi’s followers and later rejected him as a false prophet when he converted to Islam rather than be killed for his Jewish faith; none of this is clearly described. Jacob has returned to Pilitz looking for Sarah’s bones to take back to Israel, where he and his son have established happy, respected lives. The novel’s third section “The Return” is the most confusing because Singer suddenly describes how Jacob has a unique personality and chooses his own way rejecting the ways of others, which has made him an oddball, but one who is considered very devout and maybe one of the thirty-six honorable men who sustain the world’s just functioning. Such details at this point in his life is a bizarre way to conclude the novel, especially since his life as a follower of Zevi and afterwards is never described. Whether this section is intended to justify his “conversion” of Wanda, or explain how his sorrow and regret led him to follow Zevi, is never clear. Instead Singer describes that when Jacob returns for Sarah’s bones, he refuses offers of hospitality and stays in the poorhouse, where its uncleanliness means he can’t perform his prayers; overnight he becomes ill and quickly dies. <br /><br />Although the novel is based on a very romantic idea with two likeable, well-developed main characters, and sections of beautiful natural description, it is overwhelmed by factual details, repetitive theological arguments, anecdotes about Polish peasant life and Jewish traditions and experiences. It lacks a firm structure and editorial sense how many anecdotes about Jewish demons and Polish evil spirits a novel needs. For readers seeking a glimpse into pagan and Jewish peasant culture, there are interesting stories, but for a well-organized, enthralling novel on Zevi’s movement, a better choice is Singer’s Satan in Goray. Superb short stories about pre-World War II European Jewish life are in The Spinoza of Market Street, which contains many beautifully developed incidents and episodes similar to those in this novel.</span>
