  <span id="freeText14981153404179954715" style="display:none">A tough read, translated from the original, written in the mid 20th century in Yiddish and based on old Jewish folk tales. It is set in 17th century Poland in the wake of a Cossack attack and pogrom that sees the central character, Jacob, enslaved in the mountains after his family are massacred. He falls in love with his Gentile master's daughter and this is their story. Neither the Gentile Poles nor most of the Jews come away from this well. With the former the peasantry are painted as almost bestial, while the landowners are hedonistic. With the Jews there is a repeated sense of their ritual purity laws are more important than how they treat human beings, feeding in to some of the unhelpful stereotypes of Jews that feeds antisemitism. But it paints a vivid picture of this period and place, with all its superstitions and prejudices, and offers a strong sense of why 300 years later this area was ground-zero for some of the worst episodes of the Holocaust.</span>
