<span id="freeTextContainer7090717018665591609">Theme: Continue to be Jewish after the Holocaust. <br/>The Slave is really about the Holocaust. The question that is raised is: Does God really exist? And is it worthwhile to stay Jewish?<br/>Jews didn&apos;t fight back, they were not violent, they were spiritual. <br/>It&apos;s a parallel history like The Crucible (Arthur Miller). Miller was afraid of being punished (McCarthyism). For Singer it would have been too painful to write about the Holocaust. He had lost his family and he could only deal with that indirectly. </span>
  <span id="freeText7090717018665591609" style="display:none">Theme: Continue to be Jewish after the Holocaust. <br />The Slave is really about the Holocaust. The question that is raised is: Does God really exist? And is it worthwhile to stay Jewish?<br />Jews didn't fight back, they were not violent, they were spiritual. <br />It's a parallel history like The Crucible (Arthur Miller). Miller was afraid of being punished (McCarthyism). For Singer it would have been too painful to write about the Holocaust. He had lost his family and he could only deal with that indirectly. <br />Other theme: Understanding Judaism. At first Jacob's knowledge is formalistic, later less formal, more spiritual, less bound by the letter of the law and more about the spirit behind the law. <br />He sleeps with Wanda, there's a spiritual base for this. The novel redefines Judaism and endorses Jacob's new interpretation of Judaism. <br />In the end he has become a saint, a holy man. And Wanda is now in the Jewish cemetry, God has included her. <br />Singer admires the Jews for still being Jewish. In spite of all their suffering they are still loyal. It would have been easier to become Christians or atheists. So the novel is an endorsement of the continuation of the Jewish identity. <br />Towards the middle of the novel Jabcon begins to doubt God. In the last part he learns to accept. He accepts that we can't answer the question why all this happened. He is more religious at a higher level. <br />(This novel was part of the course: Jewish-American Literature in the Post-War Period. Dr. Paul Gabriner, Amsterdam University 2005)</span>
